{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656654"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18755"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18755"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80409"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11487"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18755"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7677"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10485"},{"type":"tags","id":"10502"},{"type":"tags","id":"11278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26593"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80409"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe proximal tubule of the nephron reabsorbs approximately 65% of filtered sodium and water. A significant portion of this reabsorption occurs through the spaces between epithelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes paracellular reabsorption in the proximal tubule?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vesicular transport across cells","Facilitated diffusion via carrier proteins","Passive movement through tight junctions","Secondary active transport using sodium gradient","Active transport through membrane channels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is \u003Cstrong\u003Epassive movement through tight junctions\u003C/strong\u003E. Paracellular reabsorption occurs between epithelial cells through relatively leaky tight junctions, driven by electrochemical gradients and solvent drag. This process does not require energy or specific transport proteins.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport through membrane channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Channels facilitate diffusion and do not use energy directly\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion via carrier proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Paracellular transport occurs between cells, not through cellular transport proteins\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVesicular transport across cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes transcellular transport, not paracellular movement between cells\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary active transport using sodium gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - While sodium gradients drive some reabsorption, paracellular transport is purely passive\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe proximal tubule\u0027s leaky tight junctions allow significant paracellular reabsorption of water, sodium, chloride and other small solutes without expending cellular energy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paracellular reabsorption occurs through tight junctions between epithelial cells without using energy or transporters.","The proximal tubule reabsorbs most filtered sodium and water via paracellular transport due to its leaky tight junctions.","Paracellular transport is driven by electrochemical gradients and solvent drag."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18755"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T16:36:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T16:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11487"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"